A judge is unlikely to reject the customer's claim for extra money. To get extra money, the customer must show that the store manager acted with a bad intention and did not care about the harm that could happen. The customer must also show that the store manager's actions were very bad.

The customer can argue that the store manager should have known that not cleaning the spill would be bad because many customers had slipped and fallen on the same thing before. Even though the store manager knew this, he still did not clean the spill.

It is not clear if the customer's actions were very bad. However, it is possible to say that they were bad because the store manager did not take care of the safety of his store.

On October 13, 2009, an employee told the store manager about the applesauce spill. The manager said he did not have time to deal with the problem. Another employee also told the manager about the spill, but he said the same thing. At 5:30 pm, the customer slipped and fell on the spill and got hurt.

Before the customer's accident, five other customers had slipped and fallen at the store in 2009. Now the customer is suing the store for money to pay for her injury. We are looking at whether to ask the court to throw out the part of the lawsuit that asks for extra money.

In California, a customer can get extra money if the store manager acted with "oppression, fraud or malice." Malice means acting with a bad intention or doing something very bad on purpose. If the store manager did not act with a bad intention, but his actions were very bad and he did not care about the harm that could happen, the customer may still get extra money.

A court has said that conduct is malicious when the person knows that their actions could cause harm and they do nothing to stop it.

Four years ago, I studied Islam at CBC.  A big question in our class was: Is Islam a hostile religion? I think this question is even more important now than before.  Since 9/11, I have seen the media change from being against Islam to being very friendly.  In 2001, a presidential candidate with a Muslim background would not have been elected. 

I find the story of the Prophet interesting.  His biography says he was a kind and humble man.  But this does not fit what I thought I knew about him.  I thought he forced people to join Islam.  He would win battles and then make other people join his religion.  But the biography says he was a kind leader.  People came to him because they believed in him.

There are some similarities between the teachings of Jesus and the miracles of Muhammad.  One example is when Muhammad made food for many people and there was still enough.  This way of writing makes me think the authors wanted Muhammad to seem like a kind and special person.  But it makes me think they are trying to take away from Jesus. 

I also do not like that many stories in the biography are not from direct witnesses.  The stories are from people who heard from others.  This makes the stories seem less true.

I have a problem with the biography because it makes Muhammad seem like a perfect and kind person.  But history says he was not that way.  I think Muslims should know the truth about Muhammad's past.

The ideas of Jesus and what he believed in were left behind in the growth of Christian thought after his death. If we look at the history of Christianity, we see a trend of it moving away from its beginnings. It seems that today, more people are becoming aware and thinking in a more modern way.  Most of the population still believes in traditional ideas and will not accept new thoughts. But those who know about history will become more aware in the future. They will want to know about the ideas that were added to Christianity and compare them to what Jesus really said. This will take a long time, but it will happen. People will go back to the original ideas of Jesus. They will remove the ideas that were added later. It will be like turning back time. Finally, people will follow the ideas of Jesus as if it were his time. The church will still be strong, but people will think and believe the same way.

This is not the first time something like this happened. Many years ago, Christians were persecuted by the Roman Empire. But the empire later became Christian. Our country used to be against African-Americans, but now we have African-American leaders. Something similar will happen with Christianity. It will go back to its beginning and people will think the same way. This will happen because people will start to see Jesus' words as symbols, not as exact words. If we go back in time, we see that there was only one main idea: Judaism. It was the main idea that started Christianity. By the time the Romans took control of Jerusalem, in 63 B.C.E., the Jews had many different ideas. They were divided into groups like the Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, and Zealots.

The Jungle shows that people are often selfish and do not think about others. They only want to make their lives better and do not care about people who are less fortunate. We see this in the owners and managers of big factories. They want to grow their business and make more money, no matter what. They do not care if their actions hurt people or animals.

The factories are very dirty and make a lot of pollution. The smoke from the factories goes high into the air and hurts people and animals. The owners also do not care about the workers who make them rich. They make the workers work very long hours and pay them very little. The workers have no protection and are treated very badly.

The book says that the workers in these factories are like slaves. They have no money and no choices. They are forced to live in poor conditions and work in bad factories. The owners and managers are very powerful and do not care about the workers.

The Jungle shows us that people in charge often think only about themselves and their money. They do not think about the people who are less fortunate and need help.

Many writers use different ways to make their readers feel a certain way about important subjects. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses many of these techniques in his book The Great Gatsby. He pairs words together to make readers feel a certain way about a subject. Some times he uses a word and a color, but they do not usually go together. He uses this to make readers remember a feeling when they see the color later.

Fitzgerald uses this technique with many colors. He gives meaning to colors like gold, green, white, and red. In The Great Gatsby, he builds up the meaning of white and gray. He makes white a nice color and gray an old color. He starts this in the beginning of the book. Many people are always wearing white. They include Daisy and Jordan. People also wear white when they are important. Nick wears white clothes to a party. Tom wears a white shirt to meet Myrtle.

Fitzgerald also uses white and gray to describe everyday things. He makes readers see these colors in many things. People are in white when they are young. Old people are in gray. He makes readers see these colors in many things like houses, cars, and even dogs. When people are important, they are in white. When people are old, they are in gray.

After he makes the meaning clear, Fitzgerald uses these colors to show readers that some things are not important. He does this with a character named Daisy. He stops using white and gray for a while. Then he uses them again to make readers see Daisy as not special. She wears a white dress to a party. He also writes about her fur having a gray color. He makes her seem like just a person, not a special person.

Fitzgerald uses this technique a lot in the book. He makes readers see colors and remember how they feel. He uses colors to make readers remember a feeling about a character or a subject.

San Diego County is a good place for growing food. The weather is mild and sunny. Many kinds of crops grow here, including tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, peaches, lemons, berries, and peppers. People in the area like to buy food from local farms. There is a big demand for organic food from these farms. Many people are on a waiting list to buy from these farms. Organic eggs and milk are also popular. Some farms give tours and let people walk on the land to see the wildlife.

Organic farming can be good for the land and the animals. It does not use chemicals that can harm the soil and water. But organic farming is more expensive than farming with chemicals. It needs more work and money to remove weeds and pests and to make the soil healthy. A small organic farm is not as efficient as a big farm. It also costs more to plant cover crops and to control the growth of plants.

The land we are talking about is near the town of Potrero in San Diego County. It is 160 acres of land with chaparral, grass, and oak trees. This land is next to the Cleveland National Forest. The plan for the area considers over a hundred kinds of plants and animals. Some of these plants and animals are in danger of disappearing. Others are getting fewer in number and may soon be in danger.

This land was home to Native Americans many years ago. After that, it was used for grazing cattle and for cutting wood. The land was part of a small farm a long time ago.

I looked at a real estate website and found a piece of land like this. I also looked at government programs to see what a small farmer could do to make farming cheaper and better for the wildlife. I used a local organic farm as an example of what someone farming this land might try to do.

Culture plays a big role in any negotiation. Culture is not one thing, and it is not the same everywhere. It is not uniform and it is not the same for everyone. We should not say things like "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are accommodating." These statements are too broad and too simple.

When we talk about a culture, we should think about what it means and how it will affect the talks. We should try to understand the culture, not judge it or try to change it. We can do this by learning about its history and its values. We should respect the culture and its traditions, especially if we are in a weak position.

We should also remember that culture is not just about countries. Companies have their own culture. For example, a company might expect employees to work long hours or have a relaxed schedule. We can see a company's culture in how its employees dress, how they talk to each other, and who they hire.

Values are also important. Values tell us why people do things. If saving face is important in a culture, a negotiator will not want to make their company or leader look bad. If a culture values a strong bargain, a negotiator will not want to agree too quickly. Knowing these things can help us be a better negotiator.

It is also important to learn about the person we are negotiating with. This can help us make the talks more effective.

A long time ago, a wise person in the Bible wrote, "The fool has said in his heart, 'There is no God.'" This idea is similar to the thoughts of two other important thinkers, St. Anselm and Thomas Aquinas. They both try to prove the existence of God. To compare their ideas, we will assume they both believe in the God of the Bible.

We will look at the ideas of St. Anselm first. He says that we can find the truth about God inside our own minds. He thinks that if we think about God, we will understand that God must exist. This idea is based on faith. Faith is trusting in something that we can't prove with facts.

Now, let's look at the ideas of Thomas Aquinas. He thinks that we can prove the existence of God using reason and facts. He doesn't believe in faith. Instead, he uses five different kinds of logic to show that God must exist. These kinds of logic are change, cause and effect, something being possible or not possible, levels of perfection, and harmony.

For example, if you have a puzzle and you know you are missing one piece, you can figure out what the missing piece must look like without seeing it. This is similar to how Aquinas uses logic to show that God must exist.

While both Anselm and Aquinas make good points, neither of them gives us a complete idea of why God must exist. We can only understand their ideas fully by accepting their point of view. However, this can make it difficult to compare their ideas because they are based on different kinds of thinking.

A long time ago – about two thousand five hundred years ago – a famous teacher named Buddha was born. He was a prince at the time. Later in life, he gave up his life of luxury and found a deeper meaning. This led to the creation of Buddhism, a major world religion. Over time, Buddhism has changed and looks different today from how it did when Buddha was alive. This can be seen in the country of Sri Lanka. It is a Theravada nation where a special ceremony called the water-cutting ceremony is held every year. Both monks and laypeople participate in this ceremony, which has some spiritual meaning. But Buddha did not teach about any holiday like this.

There are many differences between the way Buddhism was in the past and the way it is now. These differences come from inside the Buddhist community and from outside. The Buddhist community has had to change its teachings over time because of these forces.

There are some important words to know for this discussion. "Internal" means something that comes from inside the Buddhist community. "External" means something that comes from outside. "Hostile" means something that harms the Buddhist community. "Benign" means something that does not harm or help the Buddhist community.

First, let's look at the basic ideas of Buddhism – the ideas that are important to the religion. Buddhists seek help and protection from three things: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is a set of teachings. It includes a collection of texts called the Tripitaka. The Tripitaka has three parts: the Sutta Pitaka, the Vinaya Pitaka, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka. The Sutta Pitaka has speeches, the Vinaya Pitaka has rules for life, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka has ideas about the world and the universe. Important ideas include Anatta – there is no soul, Dukkha – life is suffering, and Anicca – everything is always changing. When you understand these ideas, you can end the cycle of death and rebirth, which is called Sansara. You will also end lobha – desire, dosa – hatred, and moha – delusion. For this to happen, you must become enlightened. In the Vinaya Pitaka, there are rules for how to live your life. For non-monks, there are five rules: do not kill, do not lie, do not steal, do not have sex with someone you are not married to, and do not take drugs. For monks, there are many more rules to follow. The most important idea in Buddhism is the four noble truths. The first truth is that life is suffering. The second truth is that attachment causes suffering. The third truth is that suffering can be overcome.

The United States and Mexico had a long rivalry that lasted 57 years.  It started in 1836 and ended in 1893.  They had many problems during this time.  The worst time was the Mexican-American War.  The United States attacked and defeated Mexico.  This war happened from 1846 to 1848.  The United States then got Texas and the Southwest as new land.  They had other fights, but they stopped before World War I.  The two countries had many differences.  They disagreed on things like religion, culture, and way of life.  They also had different ideas about what was important.  This is common when two countries share a border.  They often fight over things like land and resources.

This is like many other countries that fight with their neighbors.  The United States and Mexico are not alone.  Other countries near the United States have had good relationships.  This is true for the United States and other countries in Latin America.  Many countries have had problems with each other because of their beliefs.  In the past, Americans were against the Catholic Church and monarchies.  This is like the Cold War between the United States and the Soviet Union.  But the United States and Mexico's problems were about religion, not politics.  They got these feelings from their past colonial rulers, the English and Spanish.  This made it hard for them to be friends.

The United States and Mexico had 17 problems during this time.  Most of them were about land and the border.  There were fights over border raids and other frontier problems.  The United States and Mexico had to use their armies to stop these problems.  As time went on, Mexico became more dependent on the United States.  This helped the rivalry end.  The United States stopped trying to take land from Mexico and started to help the country economically.

Fifteen years ago, I became sick with a sickness I knew nothing about. I was a nurse at the time. I chose nursing to feel safe and secure. Many people told me this job would always be available because people will always be sick.

My dream was to be a scientist or journalist. But I chose nursing. Now I am 46 years old and unable to work. I get money from the government, but it is not enough. I have no money of my own. Every day is a struggle.

I am grateful to my family and friends for their help. Without them, I would not have made it. When disaster strikes, you do not feel strong. My point is that disasters can happen in life. We cannot prepare for everything.

We need to stop relying on big government. But instead of building shelters, we should learn to trust each other. We should help one another and ask for help when we need it.

Conservatives talk about rugged individualism, but our ancestors did not succeed alone. They had compassion, respect, and shared their resources. The pioneers who crossed the country in wagons did not make it alone.

Be prepared. I have a kit with first aid supplies and food. I also have a plan for a disaster. But it is also important to know your neighbors. Get to know them and ask for help if you need it.

Scientists want to know why living things change over time. Are there rules that help decide what kind of changes happen? Although a scientist named D'Arcy Thompson said in 1917 that it is hard to use math to understand simple living things, scientists are now using math to study how certain animals grow and change. They are studying a group of animals called mollusks. Our study is looking at how math can help us understand how these animals change as they grow.

We used a special kind of X-ray picture to study the shells of these animals. We made numbers from these pictures that can be used to make models of the shells. We used a computer program to make these models. We used the models to make predictions about what the shells might look like. We are combining this with other studies to learn more about how these animals changed over time.

A shell is like a tube that moves through space. It turns in a circle around a center point. This center point is like a line that runs through the middle of the shell. The shell has many circles, called whorls, that grow as the animal gets bigger. The whorls are like layers that add to the shell. The last circle is the biggest circle and is called the body whorl. The other circles are called the spire. The spire is all the circles except the last one.

We can look at a shell in different ways. We can look at it from the top, the bottom, the front, or the back. The front is the usual way to look at a shell. When we look at a shell, we can count the circles. We start by looking at the shell from the top and finding the first line between two circles. We draw a line to divide the shell into two parts. We count the circles from this line. We can count them by a quarter of a circle.

A shell is like a path that the animal follows as it grows. We can make a map of this path using numbers. We can use this map to change the way the shell grows. Once we have a map, we can change the numbers to see what happens to the shell.

Indonesia's rate of baby and child death in the first year of life has not changed much in the last ten years.  The country is making progress in many areas, like water and sanitation, but it is not making progress fast enough in child and mother health.  The country still has a long way to go to meet its target goals by 2015.

There are many reasons for this slow progress.  We will look at these reasons below.  They show that Indonesia needs to improve its health system, not just specific programs.

Indonesia has made some improvement in the number of births where a trained health worker is present.  Now, 72% of births have a trained worker.  However, this includes traditional workers like midwives who do not have the training to help in emergencies.  This means that many mothers are still not getting the medical help they need.  In fact, many mothers are dying from bleeding during childbirth.

The number of children under five years old who get medical help for diarrhea has decreased.  But we do not have enough information about how well babies are being taken care of after birth.  This is a problem.

Fewer women are having C-sections than they should be.  In fact, only 4% of women are having C-sections.  The number of C-sections in urban areas is 7%, but in rural areas it is only 2%.  This shows that health services are not available equally in all parts of the country.

Another problem is that the rich can get better health services than the poor.  There is a 27% difference in the number of people using health services between the richest and poorest groups.  This is because the poor cannot afford to pay out of pocket for healthcare.

Now, we need to think about how to improve the health of babies and mothers.  Should Indonesia focus on specific programs or improve the overall health system?  One tempting option is to focus on specific programs.  These programs are often easier to understand and can bring quick results.  However, there are some problems with this approach.  Investing in one area can take money and resources away from other areas.  This can cause problems in other areas of healthcare.  For example, when many resources are sent to fight HIV/AIDS, it can be hard for other areas, like family planning, to get the help they need.

Another problem with focusing on specific programs is that they can cause confusion and waste.  When many programs work on the same area, they can duplicate each other's efforts.  This can cause problems with supplies and funding.

In Victorian novels, writers often write a lot of details and focus on the lives of the rich. Two novels, Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights, are different from this tradition. They use mystery and strange events to make the characters stronger. This helps readers understand the characters' feelings and reasons for their actions.

In Oliver Twist, the author uses strange events, like dreams, to show what's happening inside Oliver's mind. These events help readers understand what hurts Oliver and what he really knows about the world. In one part of the book, Oliver sees a shooting over and over again. He remembers it like a dream, even though it really happened. This shows that Oliver has no control over what happens to him. He cannot even protect himself when his life is in danger. This makes Oliver seem defeated. It seems that the bad people in the story are breaking him down, making him accept his unhappy life.

In another part of the book, a day seems to pass very quickly. The night comes and goes quickly, but it feels very long and quiet. It also passes quickly. This can be very sad.

These two novels use strange events to make their characters stronger. They help readers understand what the characters are thinking and feeling.

I worked with students in an after-school program about two years ago. I helped them with their studies. I was good at English and reading. A teacher asked me to help a boy named Adrian. He had trouble reading. I thought something was wrong. He knew some letters, but not others. He spoke perfect English. His mother spoke no English. She spoke Spanish. I could not speak Spanish very well. But I tried to talk to her. I realized that Adrian could read, but he did not know the English alphabet. 

I tell this story to show a problem in schools. This problem is the language barrier. It is a big problem in California. Even if a child speaks perfect English, reading can be hard. I think we all agree that this is a problem. But what do we do? I helped Adrian with English reading. But for other children, the problem is more complex. We need a solution that combines many things. 

One good idea is the dual language system. This system is good for all children. Children in dual language programs do better in school. Many people are afraid of this idea. They think it is a waste of money. But this is not true. If we use this system in all schools, all children will benefit. How do we do this? Do we need all teachers to speak two languages? No. This is not realistic. But we can have special helpers who speak two languages.

We are told from a young age that there is something greater than ourselves. Some people go to Sunday school to learn about it. Others visit the Temple or search inside themselves for answers. Most of us accept the religions our parents teach us. But some of us reject them. We choose our own path and try to understand ourselves in our own way.

My father liked cardinals. He said so one rainy day when we sat on our porch. The rain was loud on the roof and the gutters were overflowing. He looked out into the rain, lost in thought. He was thin and his hair was thinning. I felt sad and scared. I didn't want to talk about his illness because it made everything real. I hugged him and sat close to him, watching the rain.

My father died in December when I was 22 years old. He had been sick for a long time. The medicine had made him suffer, but it kept him alive a little longer. I did not want to see him die. I didn't want to watch the life that made me end. I wanted to remember my father when he was alive. I curled up in bed for three days, waiting for the news.

No one called me.

The "Gothic Novel" is an interesting combination of old and new ideas. It is called an "oxymoron for 'Old-New'" by Ian Watt. People have both criticized and praised the Gothic mode. Some say it has no depth, while others say it has a powerful "terrible sublime" effect.

The first Gothic Novel was written by Horace Walpole. His book, "The Castle of Otranto," used ideas from old romances and modern novels. Walpole combined old theatrical elements and natural scenes to create a new way of writing. He called this new style a "Gothic Story."

The Gothic genre uses ideas from medieval theater, architecture, and traditions. When Walpole wrote "The Castle of Otranto," the word "gothic" was used to describe many different things. People thought it was old-fashioned and unsophisticated compared to modern society and literature.

The combination of old and new ideas in the Gothic Novel made it popular for a long time. It was both old and new to readers who were far from the time when it was written.

One important idea in Gothic Novels is chivalry. Chivalry is a medieval idea about training a good knight. In the original Gothic Novel, "The Castle of Otranto," chivalry is both kept and changed. Chivalry is important to Gothic writers because it represents a noble knight who is brave, honorable, and competent. Writers like Walpole saw a lack of these qualities in their society. They used chivalric ideas to make the past seem better and to try to improve the present.

When Walpole wrote "The Castle of Otranto," he was worried about the future. He was in a difficult time and thought that people had lost the good qualities of the past. This idea is seen in his character, Frederic. Frederic is a prince who has suffered and is supposed to be a gallant and courteous knight. His character is an example of the Gothic trope of excess.

The supply chain is the process of moving goods from the customer's order to the final product. This process includes planning, producing, and distributing products. The idea of supply chain management was created in 1982 by Keith Oliver. It is a way to plan and control the process to meet customers' needs.

There are six key parts of a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers use these parts to provide good service to customers.

The first step in the supply chain is production. Production is the base of the supply chain. It includes when, where, and how products will be made. Managers must know what customers want. They look at the market to see what customers need.

Once managers know what customers want, they decide what products to make and how many to make. Then, they choose where to make the products and which factory will work best. They consider customer demand and satisfaction.

The next step is to plan workloads and take care of equipment. Production is very important. Every detail is important. If details are not planned, it can cost the company time and money.

[REWRITE]
The second key part of the supply chain is supply. Supply means making decisions about a company's abilities and partnerships. A company may have many parts that make a product. The manager decides which part is best for each step. They may also decide to work with other companies to make the product. This is called outsourcing. Outsourcing helps a company be fast and flexible while keeping costs low.

[REWRITE]
In a company, there are many steps to make a product. These steps are production, supply, and distribution. Managers use these steps to meet customers' needs. They plan and control the process to make it quick and efficient.

[REWRITE]
For example, I worked at Wal-Mart and Target. Both companies have plans for every step of the business. This helps employees know what to do and when to do it. Having plans makes the company work smoothly.

[REWRITE]
Supply chain management is important for companies. It helps them meet customers' needs and reduce costs. Companies like Wal-Mart and Target use supply chain management to succeed.

Hitler is alive in Burma, the sign says.

Ellen Page holds a sign in a street. It says "Hitler is alive in Burma." Burma, also known as Myanmar, is a country in Southeast Asia. The government, called a junta, is very powerful. It has been in charge since 1962. In 2007, many people protested against the government. These protests were called the Saffron Revolution. The protesters were mostly monks. They wore yellow robes. The government started to allow the monks to gather peacefully. But the situation became very bad. There was a lot of violence. The military went into the monasteries and caused trouble. Journalists from other countries were arrested and put in prison. Some were hurt. A Japanese journalist named Kenji Nagai was killed for watching a protest.

This is not new. Governments have wanted to control their people for a very long time. The ancient Romans thought their leaders were chosen by the gods. The Japanese emperor was believed to be a god. The emperor of Japan brought new ideas like small phones and a special way of dying. The president of the United States, George W. Bush, talked to a man named Ted Haggard.

We know of many bad things that have happened in history. One was the protest in Tiananmen Square in China in 1989. Many students, workers, and thinkers gathered to protest against their government. The government said few people died, but other groups said many more were killed. Another bad thing was the Rwandan genocide in the 1990s. One group of people, the Hutus, killed many others, including those who were not Hutus. The government helped them. The Nazis, led by a man named Hitler, also did bad things. They killed many Jewish people.

Duke Ellington was a famous jazz musician. He lived a long time and made many creative works. His music helped shape his orchestra. Ellington played the piano in many of his compositions, but he also wrote music that made other musicians shine. He created a framework for soloists to play freely. Ellington also wrote music with tight orchestration and unique phrases that showed the style of each musician. This helped create a special sound for each piece.

The Grove Music dictionary says Ellington used the human voice as a musical instrument throughout his career. He did this in his early work, "Creole Love Call." This song is a slow, 12-bar blues. It has six parts. Each part has a different sound.

Part 1: The voice and woodwind instruments talk to each other. The voice starts smooth and then becomes rough.
Part 2: A muted trumpet plays a solo that changes the main melody.
Part 3: A clarinet plays a big, high note with a special piano sound.
Part 4: The whole band plays like the first part, but the brass and woodwind instruments talk to each other.
Part 5: The woodwind instruments play the call and response in a high place. The brass and rhythm instruments play in a special way.
Part 6: The voice goes back to the first sound, but this time it sounds like a special instrument called the "growl."

Ellington used the voice to add color to his music. This is an example of his style.

In "Hot and Bothered," Ellington combined his skill at writing music with his ear for sound. He used two musicians, Bubber Miley and Baby Cox, to create a rich sound. "It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing)" shows how Ellington used a musician named Tricky Sam Nanton to make the music special.

She had a feeling that something was missing. This feeling would not go away. It started when she was 14 years old, during her teenage years. Three years later, at 17, she still had it. Now she wanted a person, not a thing. But she was not interested in any boys. Some boys had liked her, tried to get her attention, but none of them interested her. She often thought about this strange feeling. She tried to think of what could cause it. She thought about this for a long time, but she could not find an answer.

Her life at home was usually calm. Her parents were good people and calm. They never argued with each other. They rarely argued with her. The only times they argued was when she wanted to be more independent. She was a calm person, but she had a big personality. People liked her.

Today was not a calm day. She walked from room to room, looking for ideas. She heard a loud cry from the kitchen. Her mother was hurt. She ran to the kitchen, worried. She saw her mother on the floor, in pain. She said "Ow" many times. Her daughter helped her up and asked, "Mom, what's wrong?" Her mother said, "Ow... sweetie, I need you to take me to the hospital." The daughter helped her mother to the car and drove her to the hospital.

The hospital smelled bad, like medicine. She was too busy helping her mother to feel scared. She carried her mother inside and called for help. Doctors came and took her mother to a room. The daughter waited outside.

Her mother fell off a stool while getting something from a high cabinet.

A new study shows that eating a special kind of diet, called the Mediterranean Diet, can help lower the risk of heart disease and strokes. This diet includes more plant foods, like fruits, nuts, whole grains, and vegetables, and more fish. It also includes less animal products and saturated fats. A little bit of alcohol is allowed.

Earlier studies showed that people who ate this diet were less likely to die from heart disease. But these studies did not study strokes. In this new study, researchers looked at 74,886 women who were part of a big study of women in the US. The women ate the Mediterranean Diet for about 20 years. The researchers used a special score to measure how well the women followed the diet.

The study found that women who ate a lot of these healthy foods were less likely to get heart disease and strokes. They were also less likely to die from heart disease and strokes. The researchers used a special method to make sure that other factors, like age and weight, did not affect the results.

The study shows that eating a Mediterranean Diet can be a good way to stay healthy and lower the risk of heart disease and strokes. This diet is a good choice for people who want to eat a healthy diet.

In 2007, the United States had a big economic problem. Many people lost their jobs, and the value of homes fell. This made many big companies weak. We must ask: why did this happen, and how can we stop it? The problem started because some politicians made bad decisions. They pushed banks to lend money to people who could not pay it back. This happened because the financial system was not strong enough to handle it.

Two important government organizations, Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, were also involved. They helped banks sell these bad loans to other people. When people could not pay their loans, the banks did not have enough money. They gave the problems to the people who bought the bad loans.

The problem started in 1999. The president at that time, Bill Clinton, wanted to win his second term. He loosened the rules for lending money. This helped create the problem seven years later. A reporter named Steven Holmes said in 1999, "Fannie Mae was under pressure to give more loans to people who could not afford them." He also said that this could lead to a big problem.

Many new kinds of loans were created. These loans were called adjustable-rate mortgages and mortgage-backed securities. They tied many parts of the economy together. This made it easy for people to borrow too much money. When the housing market fell, the economy fell too.

The top five big banks in the US had $4.1 trillion of bad loans in 2007. This was 30% of the country's money. Some banks, like Bear Sterns and Lehman Brothers, failed. Others, like Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley, had to change the way they worked. Fannie and Freddie had $5 trillion of bad loans and were taken over by the government in 2008.

Exposition: A Writer's Enemy

Exposition can be a problem for writers. It is when the writer tells the reader too much information. This can make the story boring. Dr. Merlin says she often sees this in her students' work.

The rule "Show, don't tell" is well-known. But writers still make the mistake of telling too much. Dr. Merlin calls this the "devil on the shoulder." It is the voice that says to get the background information out of the way.

Exposition is telling the reader what happened. It is like a character telling another person everything about their life. In a movie, it is like a long speech. In a story, the author does the telling.

A good example is a story about a woman and her husband. The reader is told that they met, got married, and he was killed. But the story does not have time to show this. The reader does not get to see the husband's personality or how much the woman loved him. This makes the story less interesting.

A writer needs to give the reader more information about the characters. This is called "meat on the bone." It makes the story more interesting and helps the reader connect with the characters.

It is easy to get into the habit of rushing through the background information. But it is better to take the time to show the reader the characters and their relationships. This makes the story more exciting and enjoyable.

I watched two news programs from Columbus, Ohio. The first one was on NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). It was a live broadcast. The main story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio who hurt his wife. He is named Shad Hostettler. He looked very bad in his picture. They only showed his picture for about two minutes. They said he hurt his wife many times and was arrested.

The second story was about a young man named Travis Buyers. He was shot in the Sharon Woods area. He is 18 years old and was badly hurt. The police have not made any arrests yet. They are investigating.

I think they did not spend much time on the second story. I believe this might be because the man who was hurt is black. For a long time, I have noticed that when a minority person is hurt or missing, the news does not talk about it very much. But if a white person is hurt or missing, the news talks about it a lot.

The next story was about a hole in a helicopter. It was shot by a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle. The police are offering a five-thousand dollar reward for information that can help them catch the person who did it.

The next story was about the weather. There will be rain and thunderstorms on Saturday afternoon. The temperature will be in the mid to low eighties all weekend.

They also talked about a robbery at a store on Clime Road in Columbus. The man who robbed the store was black and was wearing a hoodie. They said he was about six feet tall and weighed about one hundred and fifty pounds. I think they talked about the man's color too much.

Another story was about a man named Rene Rodriguez. He is a convicted drug dealer. He was sentenced to 300 months in prison for selling a lot of marijuana from Texas to Ohio. I do not think it was important to say he is Hispanic.

There is a special connection between brothers. It is strong and hard to break. Inside this connection are many feelings: love, pride, jealousy, and anger. Brothers understand each other better than anyone else. They can see themselves in each other. When things are very bad, the true nature of this connection becomes clear. It can be good or bad. This connection comes with a great price. Understanding the feelings it brings means dealing with the results of those feelings. When a person can look at their brother and see themselves, they see who they really are. In their actions and the results of those actions is where their true character is found.

The story "The Scarlet Ibis" shows this idea. Two brothers go on a journey. It is a wild and vivid journey. Bitter disappointment and great pride come together in a big way. Only one brother survives. The story is told through the main character, Doodle, and his brother. The narrator helps us understand how they feel and see the world.

The main character's feelings are about his pride. He wanted a brother who could do what he did. He wanted someone to play with, to run with, and to climb with. But his brother, Doodle, was very sick. He might not live very long or do the things the main character wanted. This made the main character very unhappy. He even thought about hurting his brother. But when Doodle smiled at him, he felt something good. This shows that the main character loved his brother too.

The human brain is a complicated, creative system. It processes information in many ways. 

At first, people thought the brain worked like a wax tablet. Later, they thought it worked like a book. Now, many people think it works like a computer. But these comparisons are not perfect. They can lead to mistakes.

The brain gets information from our senses. Our senses change physical things like touch and light into electrical signals. These signals are changed and changed again by the brain in bottom-up and top-down processes. 

Imagine you see a black box on a white background. Bottom-up processing makes a simple picture of the box. It says the box is black and has edges. Top-down processing helps you understand it's a box. It's not just a hole in the white background.

The brain decides which signals are important. It chooses which processes to use. For example, when you look at your shoes, you don't notice every blade of grass. But you notice your name in a noisy room.

The brain has different kinds of memory. It has sensory memory, working memory, and long-term memory. First, the brain puts information into memory. There are many ways to do this. For example, words can be stored based on how they look, how they sound, or what they mean.

The brain keeps information in memory. Some studies show that working memory is like a temporary loop of electrical signals. Long-term memory is like the structure of proteins.

There are many ways to understand how the brain organizes knowledge. Some ideas come from how people remember things. Others come from computer science. Others come from the way the brain works at a physical level. One idea is that the brain is like a network of connected ideas. For example, the idea of a "chair" is connected to the idea of a "table" and "wooden".

Aldous Huxley criticized the dangers of technology and capitalism in his novel Brave New World. He created a society where people value community above the individual and are conditioned to seek happiness above all else. The citizens are controlled by a powerful leader called the World Controller. A close look at the book shows Huxley's concerns about the growing power of technology and capitalism.

Huxley used ideas from Marxism to criticize capitalism. He used words like "homogeny" and "reification" to show that the people in the book are forced to follow one idea. This idea is called false consciousness. It means that the common people do not understand their place in society and are more interested in their own success. The people in the book are controlled by the World Controller and are not allowed to think for themselves. They are forced to want things they do not need, like consumer goods.

The people in the book are divided into different classes, like Delta, Gamma, and Alpha. These classes have no power to decide for themselves. They are controlled by the World Controller and are forced to do what they are told. This is an example of hegemony, where one group has power over all the others. The people in the lower classes do not know they are being controlled, and the people in the upper classes do not care.

In the book, people do not form close relationships with each other. The characters are not developed and are only interested in their physical appearance. This shows that technology and capitalism are taking away people's freedom to think and feel. People are only interested in what others think of them and are not allowed to express their true emotions.

The people in the book are happy to follow the rules and stay in their place in society. This shows how capitalism can control people's minds and make them obedient. Huxley was warning us about the dangers of technology and capitalism and how they can take away our freedom.

I have been a student at University Park for two and a half years. Getting around campus can be a problem. My first year, I was in East Halls, which is far from the center of campus. I had to walk to class in Willard building, which took about 25 minutes. The weather was often bad, which made it even harder.

I talked to an older student. They told me that not long ago, the East Halls were separated from the rest of the school by empty land. Now, that space has buildings, sports fields, and apartments. As the campus grows, it gets harder to get from one place to another.

The best solution is to use a bike. But a bike is not enough. Students must ride it, and the campus must be good for bicyclists. A friend of mine started riding again. He said, "Bikes are great. They are the best way to get around." Bicycling is good for your body and is the most efficient way to travel. I live off campus, near the center of campus. I have class in Thomas building, which is 25 minutes away by foot. But with a bike, it takes only 5 minutes.

Pollock Road is the best way to get to Thomas building, but it is not easy. There are things to say for walking too. But I am too busy to walk. If I did not have a bike, I would have to walk. Walking to Thomas every day would take 30-40 minutes. That is a lot of time. I need all my time for classes, appointments, and other things.

original_texts:
Culture plays a significant role in any negotiation. Culture can be defined as much by what it is not as what it actually is and what it signifies. Culture is not homogenous, nor is it a specific thing. It is also not singular or uniform. Statements such as “all Russians are stubborn” or “all Japanese are accommodating,” are inherently broad and overly simplistic. While the understanding of a culture’s generalizations are appropriate, it is much more productive to a negotiator to understand the significance of a culture to the matter at hand, and how that culture’s attitude can and will affect the table talks. When one approaches a foreign culture, one experiences it in a way that is relatable to his own culture, and comparisons necessarily arise. 

Attempting to understand a foreign culture or mindset can involve anything from studying its history to realizing its prejudices. Rather than judging or attempting to change a culture, one must simply accept it for what it is, and work within its boundaries, especially within the scope of negotiation, and most especially if one comes to the table with a weaker bargaining position. Likewise, if a negotiator finds himself on “away” territory, a respect for traditions and beliefs can only help in getting over any cultural barriers and move the negotiation forward.

It is important to note that culture does not necessarily limit itself to a national/international dichotomy. Most companies within a given nation establish their own corporate culture. For instance, a corporate culture might emphasize long hours in the office or a more relaxed schedule. Evidence of a corporate culture can be seen in employee dress codes, in communication style (direct v. indirect communication, delegation of duties), and hiring practices. Some companies encourage philanthropy at any level from employees, others restrict it to “company approved” charities or fundraisers. One need only look at the differences in American corporate culture from company to company (and indeed, intra-company diversity exists even from region to region, urban to suburban environments included) to appreciate the diversity of thought that can reside within a particular societal culture. Certain cultures are not nearly as stratified as American culture, and may appear more uniform to an outsider, but a similar exterior is simply a sign to dig deeper. 

Values are even more important to understand, because they provide the why of a culture. If saving face or communal harmony are valued within a culture, it is certain that a negotiator will not publicly shame his company or his superior in order to succeed at the negotiation table. Likewise, a negotiator from a culture which gives greater weight to a hard-driven bargain will not necessarily be driven to settle at the earliest opportunity. Taking these generalities into consideration is important before one gets to the negotiating table. However, a negotiator is well-served to learn something about his opponent on a personal level in order to make the negotiation effective.

“The fool hath said in his heart, ‘There is no God.’” The preceding quotation is seen first in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible, and is found at the beginning of St. Anselm’s argument regarding the existence of God. This belief seems to also be held by the other author whom we will be discussing, Thomas Aquinas. Because each of their arguments is in defense of the same concept, and our challenge is to determine who’s is the better of the two, we must, for sake of brevity, begin with the presumption that they are both correct in their belief in the existence of God, specifically the God of the Bible. To allow for a God-type figure that may not resemble the one in whom our two authors believe would not permit us to appropriately compare their two arguments, as they are essentially in defense of one specific concept of God. That being said, I would suggest that while each of them brings up valid points, neither truly provides a holistic basis for belief in God.
	To illustrate this point, we will first examine the basic argument of St. Anselm. Anselm’s passage reflects a path of gaining understanding through faith, looking within one’s self to find proof of God. He explains that because God exists within our understanding, we cannot effectively conceive his nonexistence. While this concept, when spelled out in his terminology, is a bit tedious and at times unclear, the basic gist of it is that the proof for God lies within one’s own mind. St. Anselm is suggesting to us that we needn’t go beyond the confines of our own soul to find truth about God, but that the existence of this being is found to be true simply by examining that which we inherently know to be true within our own minds. Foreign evidence is presumably unnecessary. This concept of accepting that for which there is not an irrefutable body of empirical evidence is often referred to within Christian texts as faith.
	This idea is very different from that held by St. Thomas Aquinas. Aquinas instead suggests that the existence of God can be proven entirely through reason and empirical evidence, with no need for faith of any kind. Such an idea would be beneficial in evangelism, an important element of Christianity, because it would enable the recruiting of new converts without any dependency upon their willingness to accept something that cannot be proven. They could instead be persuaded by logic alone. St. Thomas elaborates on five different logical arguments supporting the existence of God: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. In each he essentially demonstrates that the proof of God lies in the logical necessity for God. If you are told that that you are missing one puzzle piece, and assemble the rest of the puzzle, logic dictates that you can know of the features and the existence of the missing piece without having to see it.

Many authors use different ways to give their readers a certain feeling or attitude toward
important subjects. Some of these techniques are more effective than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses
many of these different techniques in his novel The Great Gatsby. Sometimes, Fitzgerald pairs an
adjective and a noun together that do not usually fit that way to give readers a certain aura around a
subject. Other times, he applies meaning to a symbol, and then uses it for this same purpose.
Fitzgerald uses this last technique with many colors, including gold, green, white/gray and red/pink. In
his novel The Great Gatsby F. Scott Fitzgerald builds up meaning for colors, namely white/gray and
red/pink then later uses that meaning to give readers a certain reminder of a feeling around an
important object.
The meaning Fitzgerald builds up and uses for white/gray is uniformity, with white being a bit
nicer and higher class and gray being more older and faded. Fitzgerald sets up this meaning in the
beginning of the novel with constant uses of both. Daisy and Jordan are constantly “in white” (8)—in
fact, everyone is always wearing white: Nick wears “white flannels” (41) to Gatsby’s party, Tom wears
a “white shirt” (36) when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine is “powdered milky white” (30). In fact, the
only time people are not wearing white is when Nick is getting his impressions of Gatsby’s party: “the
halls... are gaudy with primary colors” (40). Fitzgerald further defines these two colors in coloring
many common, unimportant subjects these colors: as Nick goes to work, he goes “down the white
chasms of lower New York” (56), the names of people at Gatsby’s parties are now “gray names” (61)
on Nick’s timetable, Catherine’s apartment is “one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses”—
uniformity (28). He also describes plain or common people or places as white or gray: Jordan and
Daisy had a “white girlhood” (19) together, there are “gray cars” and “gray land” (23) in the valley of
ashes, the “Italian child” in the railroad is “gray” (26), and the dog-seller is “a gray old man” (27).
After Fitzgerald adds enough meaning to white/gray, he uses them to signify unimportance or
uniformity to certain subjects. This using colors to show readers something first starts with Daisy.
After a long time without any significant use of either of these colors, Fitzgerald comes out describing
Daisy as “dressed in white” in “a little white roadster”; readers begin to see Daisy as less of a character,
more like just a uniform addition, something that Gatsby wants and longs for (74). Fitzgerald uses
more of this technique around Daisy to give this impression of Daisy being a more uniform addition,
for example, there is a “gray haze of Daisy’s fur collar” (18), and she is again in a “white” (115) dress
before Tom and Gatsby’s encounter.

San Diego County is very agriculturally productive, thanks to a mild, sunny climate. Common crops include: tomatoes, citrus, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There is a substantial market for organic community supported agriculture food in the San Diego area, with many local organizations having lengthy waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also popular. Many organic farms also provide tours of their agricultural operations as well as access for hiking, birdwatching, and other recreational activities. This is the type of operation that would allow the landowner to gain the benefits of government programs while improving habitat, thus allowing recreational use and creating an opportunity for farm tours and other programs for making money or for educational purposes.  
	In addition to filling a potentially lucrative niche market, the benefits of organic farming often include greater biodiversity in plants and wildlife in the area thanks to a lack of chemicals in the soil and water. However, organic farming has greater costs than conventional farming in some ways. It requires more intensive labor and management to remove pests and weeds and fertilize the soil without chemicals, and losses are often greater than with conventional methods, while a small organic farm also lacks the efficiency of scale of large operations. Practices not related to organic farming but beneficial to wildlife may also incur greater labor costs, including planting cover crops, strategic grazing rotation, invasive species removal, and active management of plant growth to provide specific conditions such as edge habitat or patches of open ground. Thus, there are many reasons why the landowner in this example might seek financial help or expertise in maximizing both profits and habitat quality.  
The land chosen for this scenario is a parcel adjacent to the town of Potrero, in unincorporated San Diego County, California. It is 160 acres of chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland next to to the Cleveland National Forest. It lies in the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. The plan is still being reviewed, but presently considers over a hundred species of plants and animals. Many are endangered, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, several species of butterfly, and the California gnatcatcher; others are declining and may soon be listed, such as burrowing owls.
	This area was inhabited by Native Americans for untold centuries and was then settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800's. This piece of land was part of an original homestead patent and so was probably used for grazing and/or wood production for many of the intervening decades.
	 chose a piece of property from a real estate website and researched available government programs to see what options a small farmer might realistically have for mitigating costs and preserving wildlife-friendly operations.  As a model of what somebody farming this land might attempt to achieve, I located an organic farm in the same area.

There is a bond between brothers; an unbreakable, irrevocable bond. Within that bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, just to name a few. Brothers understand one another, far more than anyone else with that kind of bond, and they can only see themselves when looking at their brother. It is when a situation is at its most dire when the true nature of this bond shines through, be it good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they carry with them great a cost. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal link is dealing with the consequences that they bring. When one can look a brother in the eye and see within that person their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In their actions and the consequences of those actions is where their true character lies.  In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers explore this theme, and all of the raging emotions that accompany it. Throughout a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys set out on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother escapes with his life. The theme is expressed through direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator’s point of view, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which are heavy influences on his actions.
	The protagonist’s actions can all be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From the time he and his little brother, Doodle, first go out together, to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist feels resentment towards Doodle. He had wanted a brother whom he could teach all of his worldly skills, like “…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…” He wanted a brother who could fill the role of “…someone to race to Horsehead Landing…and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn…” Obviously these things are impossible, given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making in unlikely he would even survive. Even then, it was nearly impossible that he would ever participate in vigorous physical activity. What a blow to the young protagonist, his head filled with wild fantasies, to have all of those dreams crushed in an instant. In fact, he is even shown to bear some anger towards the small child, as he recalls beginning to contemplate killing him by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would have the presence of mind to consider infanticide? However, his heart melts when the small child smiles at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist such hope! This shows that his conviction probably was not very strong. In the back of his mind, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complicated, creative information-processing system. As technology advanced from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain also advanced. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you learn about the brain, keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited and can lead to erroneous conclusions.
Information processing starts with input from the sensory organs, which transform physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the algorithms of the brain in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing puts together very simple information such as color, orientation, and where the borders of the object are – where the color changes significantly over a short space – to decide that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the decisions made at some steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. Top-down processing in this example might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.
Once information is processed to a degree, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name, even when spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results of processing are modulated by attention repeatedly.
In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. There are types of encoding specific to each type of sensory stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to what the printed word looks like, phonemically, referring to what the word sounds like, or semantically, referring to what the word means. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short period of time. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain types of proteins.
There are numerous models of how the knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on the way human subjects retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others based on neurophysiology. The semantic network model states that there are nodes representing concepts, and that the nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so forth.

In 2007, the United States of America fell into a crushing financial crisis. Unemployment increased, the housing market crashed, and many of America’s largest and most important corportations were left in ruin. This recession persists today, so we must ask the question: how did this crisis occur, and how can we stop it? In short, the financial crisis was created by selfish and naïve political decision-making that pressured banks and firms into issuing sub-prime loans into an already immature and unsufficient financial infrastructure. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to underwite and repackage these mortgages into CDO’s and CDS’. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks were short on capital reserve and transferred this chaos onto the repacked mortgages that they had sold, and on to the rest of the economy.
	The financial crisis had its roots in 1999 of the Clinton era, as the President was aiming for a second term in office. He sought to extend his presidential tenure by augmenting his popularity. To accomplish this the Clinton administration relaxed lending restrictions, which helped to set the grim stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later.  Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation's biggest underwriter of home mortgages, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans among low and moderate income people and felt pressure from stock holders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits.” Holmes would go on to correctly foresee the consequences of these actions: “But the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As detailed in the introduction, and as Holmes foresaw, ill-advised lending would certainly lead to the meltdown of the economy.
	Many factors combined to throw the economy into tailspin, one of which was the new and complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDO’s) were all used extensively in the years leading up to the crisis, and only served to intertwine more sectors of the economy into the housing market. This led to U.S. households, and financial markets in general, to overleverage themselves in the housing market, leaving them extremely vulnerable to even small changes in price. 
	Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were spited. The top five U.S. investment banks all together reported $4.1 trillion dollars of mortgage debts in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the USA’s GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold exceptionally cheap, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subjected to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in mortgage debt, and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition.  That place in your story where you stretch your little writer's wings and take flight, astounding one and all with your magnetic, nay magical prose.  Or the part where your readers fall asleep and/or hit the "Back" button while cursing your name.  Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her monitor when she finds herself in the middle of Too Much Information, and not even in the fun way.

Exposition is not your friend.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still stumbles into long passages of text where nothing happens, or worse, too much.  Exposition is the little devil sitting on your shoulder that says to get the history out of the way to get to the good parts (not to be confused with the devil sitting on the other shoulder urging the author to tell her audience every single detail of the childhoods of each character).

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in simple prose.  In film, the exposition happens when one character tells another a core-dump of information ala "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."  In fiction, the author's doing the telling.

An example is in order.  As you are reading a story, you are told that the heroine met her beloved at such a place and time, that they were married in a gala fashion, and that her husband was murdered in front of her eyes.  You would not expect this entire sequence to take two pages, during which time both he and she only get two lines of dialogue each.  You would expect the author to spend some time on the husband's character, evidencing by his speech and manner how deeply he loves his wife, and you would equally expect the heroine to show through big and small ways how much his presence in her life changed and enriched her (especially if the story were to tell you flat out later that this was the case).  A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally involved with his fate and would give you insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts and beliefs and dreams as reflected through the prism of his eyes, and so on.  You would mourn his death with her, and so grow more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect meat on the simple bone of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that meat.  (*looks at metaphor, sighs, plunges onward*)  Sometimes it is tempting to rush past certain things.  Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, and he's the night manager of a gas station now, and he was married twice, no kids, likes to go fishing on the weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

An ETF, or exchange traded fund, is a security that is designed to track an index, a commodity or a basket of assets like an index fund, but is more flexible and trades like a stock on an exchange.  An ETF gives you the diversification of an index fund and the benefits of single stock ownership like the ability to sell short, buy on margin and purchase as few as a one share in any transaction.  Though these benefits are extremely attractive, the expense ratios of ETFs are far lower than those of the average mutual fund.  Unfortunately, there are some down sides, such as the need to pay a commission on any trade involving ETFs, just as you would pay on a stock order.  Another benefit of ETFs is the wide variety of funds available.  Though these benefits are clearly stated, it is always a good exercise for the savvy financial investor to evaluate whether stated benefits, like diversification, do indeed exist, and the extent to which they exist.  For the purposes of this effort, we will be examining the ETF IHF and comparing it against the top 10 holdings that comprise the ETF to determine whether the benefits of a owning a single ETF come close to the benefits of owning a diversified portfolio of the ten stocks and also whether or not there are better configurations of the same stocks that would provide a more optimal sharp ratio or return.
	In order to evaluate the ETF, it would become rather unwieldy to include every holding, therefore we have decided to include only the top ten holdings accounting for 63.58% of all the assets in the ETF.  Below are the top 10 holdings and the percentage of total assets.

	In order to gain an estimation of how well these ten stocks represent the ETF IHF as a whole, we can use the current % of assets, normalized to 100%, to  calculate the contributions of each stock to a portfolioâ€™s Beta and Return if the portfolio was made up entirely of these 10 stocks in the proportion that the ETF has established through their holdings.  The calculations of Beta and return are included in the below chart.

From the above chart it is evident that the return of a portfolio containing only the top 10 holdings is 6.11% higher than the ETF, a 16% increase in returns.  It is also evident that the Beta of the top ten holdings is .12 lower than the ETF as a whole.  From the results completed thus far, it seems that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings could provide a higher return with a lower beta.  However, there is a possibility that the means of these two portfolios may not be statistically different from each other.
	In order to evaluate whether or not these portfolios are statistically different, the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks is determined and normalized to 100% in order to compare their accumulated standard deviation to that of the ETF IHF.

Referring back to Figure 17, there was a precipitous drop in commuter log submissions in the third month of the project. That was a bit disheartening, and it is hard to say why that might have happened. With the onset of winter at a New England campus, there is clearly a drop in people commuting either by bicycle or by foot, which may account for some portion of the decline. December also marks the end of the fall semester when everyone is very busy finishing schoolwork, processing grades, and so forth. Filling out the commuter log might just have slipped off the radar screen for many folks. In addition, December brings the onset of the busy holiday season and the resulting month-long break for students and faculty, during which time many do not even need to come to campus at all. Classes then resume for the spring semester in late January, perhaps also a clue to the low number of logs for that month. But none of that really explains the low number of submissions for February. One might also conjecture that any project of this type is going to have an initial burst of energy and excitement at the outset, which might then naturally decline. In an effort to combat this trend, we created the Carpool Challenge Week, a special blitz campaign in March to try and reinvigorate the initiative, which did result in an increase in log submissions for that month. Thus, one of the challenges we experienced was how to maintain project momentum in the face of both a natural decrease in engagement, but also specifically the problem of holiday and semester breaks experienced in higher education. 
Another challenge for this project (or any alternative commuting project) is the simple fact that people enjoy the freedom, independence, and flexibility of driving their cars. This is deeply embedded in our culture. Therefore, it is essential to provide incentives for engaging in alternative modes of commuting. We gave out a lot prizes in the form of gift certificates to local restaurants, coffee shops, massage therapists, the local independent bookstore, and even some larger national chain stores. It would have been interesting to see, however, how some even larger prizes might have affected participation – such as giving away a nice bicycle, hybrid car, or electric car. This could have also helped to combat that dip in engagement the project experienced. The nature of the prizes didn’t really change during the course of the project. If the prizes, however, were to increase in value over the course of the project, that might have helped. The gift cards seemed to be more than adequate at the outset of the project, but if we had announced in December the addition of a couple of bicycles, and then in January the addition of a hybrid or electric car, one can only think that participating and engagement would have increased instead of decreasing.

In looking through the Library of Congress’s library of early Edison films, I decided to view all of the trick films, of which there were fifteen from 1895 to 1901. These films generally take advantage of creative editing to produce illusions. My film study generally focused on describing the poetics for the majority of trick films and examining the evolutionary outlier characteristics present in a few of the later films. Largely, the trick film at the turn of the century is set-bound, composed within a frontal proscenium, features no camera movement, uses long and medium shots, and adheres to the strict one shot = one film methodology. However, there are some films at the beginning of the twentieth century that dare to break these guidelines by introducing aspects such as multiple shots.
One of the most noticeable aspects that the trick films share in common is their filming in an interior set within the frame of a frontal proscenium. The camera does not move from its proscenium position to follow figures or objects. This composition was very common in early films, and drew its root from the theatre and, for trick films, vaudeville and magic acts. One of the limitations inherent in the use of the stage is that figures in trick films generally only move side-to-side, and do not walk towards or away from the camera. Take, for example, the action in the film Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900). The actors enter from the right side and move back and forth along the horizontal axis. Even as they go out of the frame, the camera does not follow them.
The frontal proscenium style of composition also means that shots tend to be long shots and, more rarely, medium shots. Close-up shots are never used in any of the trick films from the Edison catalog. This borrows from the theatre and vaudeville tradition, where the audience would see the entire performance at any given time, framed by the borders of the stage. As in most early films, the actors do not move from the middle ground towards the camera, so close-ups never occur.
Generally, most early trick films follow the pattern that one conceptual shot equals a film. This limits the length of most trick films to about a minute or less, depending on the frames per second used.
